  "prompt": "In Bhagavad Gita 18th chapter, Lord Krishna says \"Arjuna is his dearest friend\". I am curious to know if there are any stories in Arjuna's previous birth, to become Lord's dearest friend in Vishnu's incarnation as Krishna?",
  "response": "In Hindu mythology, there are a few stories that explain Arjuna's special relationship with Lord Krishna and his origin:\n\n1. According to the Mahabharata and Puranic texts, Arjuna was an incarnation of the celestial sage Nara, who was a constant companion of Narayana (Lord Vishnu). They were inseparable friends in their previous divine form.\n\n2. In one narrative, Nara and Narayana were performing intense penance, and their spiritual bond was so strong that they took multiple births together to fulfill a divine purpose.\n\n3. In another story, during a previous birth, Arjuna was a sage named Nara who had earned Krishna's deep friendship and affection through his devotion and spiritual practices.\n\n4. Some texts suggest that in a previous life, Arjuna was a devoted follower of Lord Vishnu who had performed severe austerities to be close to the Lord.\n\n5. The Pandavas, including Arjuna, are also considered partial incarnations of various celestial beings, which predestined their close relationship with Krishna.\n\nThese stories highlight the eternal spiritual connection between Arjuna and Krishna, explaining their deep friendship in the Mahabharata era.",
